cfg_fracn_sd_step_en_amode[14:14]
Injects an impulse into fracN SD accumulator. This inject a step in the feed-forward offset and as a result would create a step on the PLL phase. This feature can be useful in case of coupling between PLLs that run at exact same frequency (both at fracN)

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_amode
cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_amode[13:11]
Defines number of refclk cycles in frequency measurement during AFC calibration. Number of cycles = 2^reg For 156MHz clock and 12.5GHz DCO clock, HS counter (@Fdco/2) samples 40 cycles per refclk (=fbdiv_intgr). DTR step size is 20MHz, so to achieve accuracy of 5MHz, HS counter should reach 12.5G/5M=2500. Therefore refclk cycles = 2500/40=62.5, so 2^6 would be appropriate. use the following formula for other frequencies (Frefclk after prediv): cfg_refclk_cnt_limit = round(log2(2*Frefclk/5MHz))

Reset: hex:0x6;
[10:10]
RW

o_fracnen_h_amode
o_fracnen_h_amode[10:10]
Enables fractional ratio. Set this bit to 0 if fractional ratio is 0, else to 1. If this bit is 1 while fractional is 0 then fbclk to refclk phase won&#39;t be deterministic.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[09:00]
RW

Reset: hex:0x050;

cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_amode
cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_amode[16:9]
This signal defines the number of refclk cycles that fit in 1us. Used in VREG loop in steady-state, such that whenever DAC code is updated, we wait some time based on this counter before start sensing the comparator. Could be used potentially in the future for other timers as well. Use the following formula: Frefclk x 1usec

Reset: hex:0x9c;
[08:05]
RW

cfg_gaincal_update_rate_amode
cfg_gaincal_update_rate_amode[8:5]
This field sets the rate of adaptive feed-forward gain. Every time the modulated feedback divider ratio is 0.5 or more away from the target ratio (with frac code), the feed-forward gain loop checks the amount of change in TDC effective (after feed-forward cancelation) and based on the sign of that change it would increment/decrement the feed-forward gain. Then this register determines every how many adaptive-ffgain checks the gain will actually be updated. This technique could be useful if ratio is around 0.5, to avoid too frequent gain updates (which could cause stability problems in the loop). The adaptive ffgain loop will react every 2 ^ cfg_gaincal_update_rate gain checks

Reset: hex:0x0;
[04:01]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_amode
cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_amode[4:1]
Determines the number of refclk cycles from lock timer done until TDC turns into bang-bang mode: 2 ^ cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit.

Reset: hex:0x9;
[00:00]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_en_amode[0:0]

Reset: hex:0x0;

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_bmode
cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_bmode[13:11]
Defines number of refclk cycles in frequency measurement during AFC calibration. Number of cycles = 2^reg For 156MHz clock and 12.5GHz DCO clock, HS counter (@Fdco/2) samples 40 cycles per refclk (=fbdiv_intgr). DTR step size is 20MHz, so to achieve accuracy of 5MHz, HS counter should reach 12.5G/5M=2500. Therefore refclk cycles = 2500/40=62.5, so 2^6 would be appropriate. use the following formula for other frequencies (Frefclk after prediv): cfg_refclk_cnt_limit = round(log2(2*Frefclk/5MHz))

Reset: hex:0x6;
[10:10]
RW

o_fracnen_h_bmode
o_fracnen_h_bmode[10:10]
Enables fractional ratio. Set this bit to 0 if fractional ratio is 0, else to 1. If this bit is 1 while fractional is 0 then fbclk to refclk phase won&#39;t be deterministic.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[09:00]
RW

o_fbdiv_intgr_bmode[9:0]

Reset: hex:0x050;

o_fbdiv_strobe_h_bmode
o_fbdiv_strobe_h_bmode[14:14]
Enables sampling feedback ratio (integer+fractional) into PLL logic. Before changing feedback ratio dynamically (while PLL is running), one should deassert this bit until new ratio is udpated in registers. This is to ensure safe and synchronoius update of ratio. The feedback ratio will propagate automatically into PLL logic while PLL is off until DCO settle state is done.

Feed-forward gain for fractional mode. When o_feedfwrdcal_en_h=0, this will determine the gain. When o_feedfwrdcal_en_h=1, this will determine initial value of the gain. Use the following formula: Full rate: o_feedfwrdgain = 1/(Fdco*tdc_fine_step) Half rate: o_feedfwrdgain = 2/(Fdco*tdc_fine_step) For franN mode, tdc_fine_step is 6.5psec.

Reset: hex:0x0c;

cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_bmode
cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_bmode[16:9]
This signal defines the number of refclk cycles that fit in 1us. Used in VREG loop in steady-state, such that whenever DAC code is updated, we wait some time based on this counter before start sensing the comparator. Could be used potentially in the future for other timers as well. Use the following formula: Frefclk x 1usec

Reset: hex:0x9c;
[08:05]
RW

cfg_gaincal_update_rate_bmode
cfg_gaincal_update_rate_bmode[8:5]
This field sets the rate of adaptive feed-forward gain. Every time the modulated feedback divider ratio is 0.5 or more away from the target ratio (with frac code), the feed-forward gain loop checks the amount of change in TDC effective (after feed-forward cancelation) and based on the sign of that change it would increment/decrement the feed-forward gain. Then this register determines every how many adaptive-ffgain checks the gain will actually be updated. This technique could be useful if ratio is around 0.5, to avoid too frequent gain updates (which could cause stability problems in the loop). The adaptive ffgain loop will react every 2 ^ cfg_gaincal_update_rate gain checks

Reset: hex:0x0;
[04:01]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_bmode
cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_bmode[4:1]
Determines the number of refclk cycles from lock timer done until TDC turns into bang-bang mode: 2 ^ cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit.

Reset: hex:0x9;
[00:00]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_en_bmode[0:0]

Reset: hex:0x0;

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_cmode
cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_cmode[13:11]
Defines number of refclk cycles in frequency measurement during AFC calibration. Number of cycles = 2^reg For 156MHz clock and 12.5GHz DCO clock, HS counter (@Fdco/2) samples 40 cycles per refclk (=fbdiv_intgr). DTR step size is 20MHz, so to achieve accuracy of 5MHz, HS counter should reach 12.5G/5M=2500. Therefore refclk cycles = 2500/40=62.5, so 2^6 would be appropriate. use the following formula for other frequencies (Frefclk after prediv): cfg_refclk_cnt_limit = round(log2(2*Frefclk/5MHz))

Reset: hex:0x6;
[10:10]
RW

o_fracnen_h_cmode
o_fracnen_h_cmode[10:10]
Enables fractional ratio. Set this bit to 0 if fractional ratio is 0, else to 1. If this bit is 1 while fractional is 0 then fbclk to refclk phase won&#39;t be deterministic.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[09:00]
RW

o_fbdiv_intgr_cmode[9:0]

Reset: hex:0x050;

cfg_sigma_delta2_sel_cmode[20:20]

[19:15]

o_dither_value_cmode[19:15]
DCO Dither Override Value (in case o_dither_ovrd=1). 5 MSB of the filter fractional code (rest 4 LSBs are set to 0).

Reset: hex:0x00;
[14:14]
RW

o_fbdiv_strobe_h_cmode
o_fbdiv_strobe_h_cmode[14:14]
Enables sampling feedback ratio (integer+fractional) into PLL logic. Before changing feedback ratio dynamically (while PLL is running), one should deassert this bit until new ratio is udpated in registers. This is to ensure safe and synchronoius update of ratio. The feedback ratio will propagate automatically into PLL logic while PLL is off until DCO settle state is done.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

o_lock_criteria_cmode
o_lock_criteria_cmode[13:11]
Phase lock indicator criteria. Asserted high when phase error is less than or equal to the threshold value for: 000: 16 consecutive cycles 001: 32 consecutive cycles 010: 48 consecutive cycles 011: 64 consecutive cycles 100: 80 consecutive cycles 101: 96 consecutive cycles 110: 112 consecutive cycles 111: 128 consecutive cycles

Reset: hex:0x5;
[10:10]
RW

o_dcoditheren_h_cmode
o_dcoditheren_h_cmode[10:10]

Reset: hex:0x1;
[09:09]
RW

o_feedfwrdcal_pause_h_cmode
o_feedfwrdcal_pause_h_cmode[9:9]
This bit is for dynamically turning on and off feed forward gain adaptive mode.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[08:08]
RW

o_feedfwrdcal_en_h_cmode
o_feedfwrdcal_en_h_cmode[8:8]
Feedfward gain adaptive mode enable

Reset: hex:0x1;
[07:00]
RW

o_feedfwrdgain_cmode
o_feedfwrdgain_cmode[7:0]
Feed-forward gain for fractional mode. When o_feedfwrdcal_en_h=0, this will determine the gain. When o_feedfwrdcal_en_h=1, this will determine initial value of the gain. Use the following formula: Full rate: o_feedfwrdgain = 1/(Fdco*tdc_fine_step) Half rate: o_feedfwrdgain = 2/(Fdco*tdc_fine_step) For franN mode, tdc_fine_step is 6.5psec.

Reset: hex:0x0c;

cfg_fine_first_boost_repeat_cmode
cfg_fine_first_boost_repeat_cmode[7:5]
Determines the number of repetitions of the boost gain counter for the first stage of the fine boost. The number of overall repetitions is equal to cfg_fine_first_boost_repeat + 1 Set this to non-zero when PLL needs to lock on SSC&#39;ed refclk, to allow enough time for the boost to handle fast cap-swap.

cfg_lock_thresh_cmode[4:0]
Phase lock detect threshold. The PLL will generate plllockout when the TDC phase error is within lockthresh for a number of cycles determined by o_lock_criteria. 0 is forbidden value.

cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_cmode
cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_cmode[16:9]
This signal defines the number of refclk cycles that fit in 1us. Used in VREG loop in steady-state, such that whenever DAC code is updated, we wait some time based on this counter before start sensing the comparator. Could be used potentially in the future for other timers as well. Use the following formula: Frefclk x 1usec

Reset: hex:0x9c;
[08:05]
RW

cfg_gaincal_update_rate_cmode
cfg_gaincal_update_rate_cmode[8:5]
This field sets the rate of adaptive feed-forward gain. Every time the modulated feedback divider ratio is 0.5 or more away from the target ratio (with frac code), the feed-forward gain loop checks the amount of change in TDC effective (after feed-forward cancelation) and based on the sign of that change it would increment/decrement the feed-forward gain. Then this register determines every how many adaptive-ffgain checks the gain will actually be updated. This technique could be useful if ratio is around 0.5, to avoid too frequent gain updates (which could cause stability problems in the loop). The adaptive ffgain loop will react every 2 ^ cfg_gaincal_update_rate gain checks

Reset: hex:0x0;
[04:01]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_cmode
cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_cmode[4:1]
Determines the number of refclk cycles from lock timer done until TDC turns into bang-bang mode: 2 ^ cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit.

Reset: hex:0x9;
[00:00]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_en_cmode[0:0]

Reset: hex:0x0;

Injects an impulse into fracN SD accumulator. This inject a step in the feed-forward offset and as a result would create a step on the PLL phase. This feature can be useful in case of coupling between PLLs that run at exact same frequency (both at fracN)

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_dmode
cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_dmode[13:11]
Defines number of refclk cycles in frequency measurement during AFC calibration. Number of cycles = 2^reg For 156MHz clock and 12.5GHz DCO clock, HS counter (@Fdco/2) samples 40 cycles per refclk (=fbdiv_intgr). DTR step size is 20MHz, so to achieve accuracy of 5MHz, HS counter should reach 12.5G/5M=2500. Therefore refclk cycles = 2500/40=62.5, so 2^6 would be appropriate. use the following formula for other frequencies (Frefclk after prediv): cfg_refclk_cnt_limit = round(log2(2*Frefclk/5MHz))

Reset: hex:0x6;
[10:10]
RW

o_fracnen_h_dmode
o_fracnen_h_dmode[10:10]
Enables fractional ratio. Set this bit to 0 if fractional ratio is 0, else to 1. If this bit is 1 while fractional is 0 then fbclk to refclk phase won&#39;t be deterministic.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[09:00]
RW

o_fbdiv_intgr_dmode
o_fbdiv_intgr_dmode[9:0]
Feedback divider integer ratio Total ratio is: If cfg_dcodiv2_to_fbdiv_bypass=1 : (integer+fractional/2^32) otherwise : (integer+fractional/2^32) x 2 Default is 80 for main common PLL (refclk 156.25MHz and Fdco 12.5GHz)

Reset: hex:0x050;

o_fbdiv_strobe_h_dmode[14:14]
Enables sampling feedback ratio (integer+fractional) into PLL logic. Before changing feedback ratio dynamically (while PLL is running), one should deassert this bit until new ratio is udpated in registers. This is to ensure safe and synchronoius update of ratio. The feedback ratio will propagate automatically into PLL logic while PLL is off until DCO settle state is done.

cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_dmode
cfg_refclk_cycles_per_1us_maxcnt_dmode[16:9]
This signal defines the number of refclk cycles that fit in 1us. Used in VREG loop in steady-state, such that whenever DAC code is updated, we wait some time based on this counter before start sensing the comparator. Could be used potentially in the future for other timers as well. Use the following formula: Frefclk x 1usec

Reset: hex:0x9c;
[08:05]
RW

cfg_gaincal_update_rate_dmode
cfg_gaincal_update_rate_dmode[8:5]
This field sets the rate of adaptive feed-forward gain. Every time the modulated feedback divider ratio is 0.5 or more away from the target ratio (with frac code), the feed-forward gain loop checks the amount of change in TDC effective (after feed-forward cancelation) and based on the sign of that change it would increment/decrement the feed-forward gain. Then this register determines every how many adaptive-ffgain checks the gain will actually be updated. This technique could be useful if ratio is around 0.5, to avoid too frequent gain updates (which could cause stability problems in the loop). The adaptive ffgain loop will react every 2 ^ cfg_gaincal_update_rate gain checks

Reset: hex:0x0;
[04:01]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_dmode
cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_dmode[4:1]
Determines the number of refclk cycles from lock timer done until TDC turns into bang-bang mode: 2 ^ cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit.

Reset: hex:0x9;
[00:00]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_en_dmode[0:0]

Reset: hex:0x0;

Injects an impulse into fracN SD accumulator. This inject a step in the feed-forward offset and as a result would create a step on the PLL phase. This feature can be useful in case of coupling between PLLs that run at exact same frequency (both at fracN)

Reset: hex:0x0;
[13:11]
RW

cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_emode
cfg_refclk_cnt_limit_emode[13:11]
Defines number of refclk cycles in frequency measurement during AFC calibration. Number of cycles = 2^reg For 156MHz clock and 12.5GHz DCO clock, HS counter (@Fdco/2) samples 40 cycles per refclk (=fbdiv_intgr). DTR step size is 20MHz, so to achieve accuracy of 5MHz, HS counter should reach 12.5G/5M=2500. Therefore refclk cycles = 2500/40=62.5, so 2^6 would be appropriate. use the following formula for other frequencies (Frefclk after prediv): cfg_refclk_cnt_limit = round(log2(2*Frefclk/5MHz))

Reset: hex:0x6;
[10:10]
RW

o_fracnen_h_emode
o_fracnen_h_emode[10:10]
Enables fractional ratio. Set this bit to 0 if fractional ratio is 0, else to 1. If this bit is 1 while fractional is 0 then fbclk to refclk phase won&#39;t be deterministic.

Reset: hex:0x0;
[09:00]
RW

Reset: hex:0x050;

Used in VREG loop in steady-state, such that whenever DAC code is updated, we wait some time based on this counter before start sensing the comparator. Could be used potentially in the future for other timers as well. Use the following formula: Frefclk x 1usec

Reset: hex:0x9c;
[08:05]
RW

cfg_gaincal_update_rate_emode
cfg_gaincal_update_rate_emode[8:5]
This field sets the rate of adaptive feed-forward gain. Every time the modulated feedback divider ratio is 0.5 or more away from the target ratio (with frac code), the feed-forward gain loop checks the amount of change in TDC effective (after feed-forward cancelation) and based on the sign of that change it would increment/decrement the feed-forward gain. Then this register determines every how many adaptive-ffgain checks the gain will actually be updated. This technique could be useful if ratio is around 0.5, to avoid too frequent gain updates (which could cause stability problems in the loop). The adaptive ffgain loop will react every 2 ^ cfg_gaincal_update_rate gain checks

Reset: hex:0x0;
[04:01]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_emode
cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit_emode[4:1]
Determines the number of refclk cycles from lock timer done until TDC turns into bang-bang mode: 2 ^ cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit.

Reset: hex:0x9;
[00:00]
RW

cfg_tdcbbpd_en_emode
cfg_tdcbbpd_en_emode[0:0]
Switches TDC into bang-bang mode, based on timer (cfg_tdcbbpd_cnt_limit). If enabled, cfg_tdc_ladder_min register must be configured to 1 or greater.

Reset: hex:0x0;
